Log**: The backtrace points to a crash inside `llvm::AArch64TTIImpl::getIntrinsicInstrCost`,
which calls `llvm::BasicTTIImplBase<llvm::AArch64TTIImpl>::getIntrinsicInstrCost`. The crash
itself happens in
`llvm::ilist_detail::node_base_parent<llvm::BasicBlock>::getNodeBaseParent()`, which is a
strong indicator that the code is trying to access the parent basic block of an `Instruction`
that has not been inserted into any basic block. This typically happens with temporary or
newly created instructions that are not yet part of a function.\n\n3. **Root Cause
Analysis**:\n    - The loop vectorizer builds a `VPlan` to model the vectorized loop. The
`llvm.powi` call is represented by a `VPWidenCallRecipe`.\n    - To decide whether
vectorization is profitable, the vectorizer calculates the cost of the VPlan. This involves
calling `VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost`.\n    - Inside `VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost`, an
`IntrinsicCostAttributes` object is created to query the `TargetTransformInfo` (TTI) for the
cost. This object is populated with information about the intrinsic, including its
arguments.\n    - The arguments for this cost query are derived from the `VPValue` operands of
the `VPWidenCallRecipe`. The code attempts to get the underlying `Value*` for each
`VPValue`.\n    - For the `llvm.powi.f64.i32` call, the second argument is the integer
constant `3`. In the VPlan, this is represented by a `VPValue` that wraps a `ConstantInt`.
However, this `VPValue` does not have an \"underlying value\" set in this specific scenario.\n
- The logic in `VPWidenCallRecipe::computeCost` has a fallback: if a `VPValue` operand has no
underlying value, it tries to get the argument from the original `CallBase` instruction. This
retrieves the original `ConstantInt` `3`.\n    - The problem arises in
